<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-pop" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Defining a Population</title>
    <p>
        A <term><em>sample</em></term> is the set of observations that has been collected and is available for analysis. 
        You can open a dataset in R-Instat and view every observation in the sample. A <term><em>population</em></term>, 
        on the other hand, is the complete set of individuals, objects, or measurements about which we want to draw conclusions. 
        In most studies, the population is much larger than the sample and may even be impossible to observe in its entirety.
    </p>
    <p>
        Before collecting or analysing data, it is important to clearly define the population of interest. 
        The design of the study, the method used to select the sample, and the conclusions that can be drawn all depend on 
        the population being investigated. In practice, however, the population may not always be precisely defined, 
        particularly in observational studies where the available data determine the scope of the analysis.
    </p>
    <p>
        In some situations, identifying the population is straightforward. For example, 
        if a survey is conducted to estimate the proportion of registered voters who support a particular candidate, 
        the population consists of all registered voters, while the sample is the group of voters who participated in the survey.
    </p>
    <p>
        In other situations, defining the population requires more careful consideration. Suppose a researcher collects 
        data from 100 maize farms in a district to study crop yield. Depending on the objective of the study, 
        the population could be:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    All maize farms in the district.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    All maize farms in the country.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Small-scale maize farms only.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Maize farms with similar climatic and soil conditions.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        Each of these represents a different population, and the appropriate choice depends on the research question. 
        The sample remains the same, but the conclusions that can be drawn differ according to the population to which the 
        researcher intends to generalise the results.
    </p>
    <p>
        Throughout this book, datasets analysed in R-Instat represent samples drawn from larger populations. 
        Understanding the distinction between a sample and a population is essential because statistical inference uses 
        information from the sample to estimate unknown characteristics of the population.
    </p>  
</subsection>